  "enhanced_information": "Progesterone production in the ovary is primarily by the corpora lutea. This is supported by the standard physiological consensus that after ovulation, the corpus luteum forms from the remnants of the ovulated follicle. The primary function of the corpus luteum is to produce progesterone, which is crucial for maintaining the early stages of pregnancy until the placenta takes over. This is confirmed by the evidence path linking the structure of the corpus luteum directly to progesterone production. Other structures such as the mature follicles, corpora albicans, and stroma play significantly lesser roles in progesterone production. Mature follicles mainly focus on the maturation and release of eggs rather than progesterone production. Corpora albicans, being the degenerated form of the corpus luteum, have minimal hormonal activity. The ovarian stroma, primarily a structural component, has limited endocrine function and thus contributes minimally to progesterone production."
